name: Alex Lieberman ☕️
tweet: The work that we're doing at Morning Brew is incredible.   It will only get more impactful.   I'm so excited to pass the torch to my co-founder, and I'm more committed than ever to serve this business in the ways that both give me energy and add immense value to the company.

name: Alex Lieberman ☕️
tweet: COMMUNICATION  I want to be the greatest cheerleader for Morning Brew externally.  What we do is amazing and everyone should know about it.   Whether it be B2B events, podcasts, or my own social channels, I will storytell our evolution and impact as we continue to grow.

name: Alex Lieberman ☕️
tweet: CONTENT  I love creating content.  And I love creating content for the business builder.   I plan to triple down on Founder’s Journal and find more and better ways to serve this subset of our Modern Business Leader audience.

name: Alex Lieberman ☕️
tweet: CRM  I love meeting & learning from smart, good people.   I plan on spending time over the coming months & years building relationships with CEOs, CMOs, and great talent.  I will act as a top of funnel for the business making introductions for our revenue org, content org, etc.

name: Alex Lieberman ☕️
tweet: CULTURE  Morning Brew has a special culture.   We don’t want it to dilute as we scale from 90 to 150 to 200+ employees.   I plan on spending time monthly and quarterly working with our Head of People to ensure we do this.

name: Alex Lieberman ☕️
tweet: And to use the ship analogy, my goal, as Executive Chairman, is to be the wind at the sails of the ship that Austin is captaining.  That takes four forms:  1) Culture 2) CRM 3) Content 4) Communication

name: Alex Lieberman ☕️
tweet: That is why we are making this move.   That is why I am so confident in this decision.   And that is why I'm so optimistic about the future of this business.   Now is the perfect time for Austin to captain the ship.

name: Alex Lieberman ☕️
tweet: And as I’ve reflected, I've realized that my interests & my skills are not 100% aligned with what is required of the CEO role today.   That's why I feel so fortunate that Austin has skills and interests that do perfectly align with what is required of the CEO role today.

name: Alex Lieberman ☕️
tweet: What is required of the CEO today is different from what has been required  in the past.   It's no longer about building & brute force.   It's about operational excellence.   • Exceptional planning.  • Exceptional coordination. • Exceptional strategy tied to long-term vision.

name: Alex Lieberman ☕️
tweet: During times of evolution and momentum it is most important to ask ourselves:   “What is required of our leader today to put the business in the best position to succeed tomorrow?”   I have reflected on this question for months and discussed it with those I trust.

name: Alex Lieberman ☕️
tweet: Since January 2020…   • We 3x'd headcount to 90 • We built an allstar senior leadership team • We built a portfolio of seven products across several mediums • We built a burgeoning B2B business • We have remained profitable, while doubling revenue

name: Alex Lieberman ☕️
tweet: It is remarkable how this company has grown over the last 12 months.   We’ve long talked about this transition from newsletter business to media brand.   Well, that day is here.

name: Alex Lieberman ☕️
tweet: If you enjoyed this masterclass, check out my full @FoundersPod on curation...  here:  https://t.co/1ukBsarbNL  or here:  https://t.co/8VbzjmTNvb

name: Alex Lieberman ☕️
tweet: That is what I hope you realize about curation.   It exists everywhere, it’s as old as time and it’s really about simplifying choice and optimizing satisfaction for the customer.

name: Alex Lieberman ☕️
tweet: It curated not due to abundance of choice, but scarcity of space, stocking the shelves of its 30k-200k square foot stores.   Curation based on local preferences of the retailer’s customers was also a priority.  A Bentonville shopper has different interests than a New Haven one.

name: Alex Lieberman ☕️
tweet: Curation is all around us.   And curation is not new. That is the third misconception of this superpower.   Take WalMart as an example.   WalMart has been a master curator since its founding in 1962.

name: Alex Lieberman ☕️
tweet: Which leads to the second misconception of curation.   Curation is not just reserved for media businesses.   Think about it.   Trader Joes curates food that caters to the needs of a specific shopper.  Universities curate courses that cater to the needs of a specific student.

name: Alex Lieberman ☕️
tweet: Turns out, people will pay for smart curation AND the value of curation is going up thanks to the internet.   The internet has unlocked abundance.  With abundance comes greater need for smart curators to cut down search costs & help save you time.

name: Alex Lieberman ☕️
tweet: How could we amass this audience if none of the content is technically the first version of that story?   It's all about smart curation.   Readers don’t care that we’re not breaking news. They only care that we’re saving time they’d spend figuring out what news to care about.

name: Alex Lieberman ☕️
tweet: The first big misconception about curation is why it's actually valuable.   Given Morning Brew’s value prop is driven by curation, I can speak to this directly.   We don't break news or do original reporting in our daily newsletter, yet 3mm people trust us with their time.

name: Alex Lieberman ☕️
tweet: To appreciate the value of curation you need to understand what it is.   My definition:   The act of narrowing down choice to the things that you believe a consumer will want or should want.   Curation is about limiting choice for the sake of speed & focus.

name: Alex Lieberman ☕️
tweet: Quick agenda:   1) What is curation 2) Misconception #1 3) Internet's impact on curation 4) Misconception #2 5) Misconception #3

name: Alex Lieberman ☕️
tweet: Curation is a superpower.   It's all around us, it's old as time, and it adds value to consumers.   Yet people fail to understand it.   It's time for a Curation masterclass 👇

tweet: + you can still draft off the infiniteness of the internet while helping consumers choose.  Amazon is the perfect example.  It gets more powerful the more products offered, but curates for customers as well:  - Search - Recs based on past purchases - Organization by category

name: Alex Lieberman ☕️
tweet: Curation is a new phenomenon for a lot of people, but it’s always been around us.  Walmart is a curator of physical goods.  Trader Joe’s is a curator of food.  ETFs are curators of financial securities.  Curation brings customer-focused scarcity to infinite selection.

name: Alex Lieberman ☕️
tweet: 8) ConvertKit attracted great talent in two ways:   • Being a distributed business earlier than most (since 2013) which offered employees total flexibility  • Building in Public earlier than most to establish brand affinity

name: Alex Lieberman ☕️
tweet: 7) Nathan hired someone to run product at ConvertKit.   He said that firing himself from the role was one of the best decisions he made for the business and was something he probably should have done earlier.

name: Alex Lieberman ☕️
tweet: 6) Podcasting isn't just for external use.   ConvertKit has an internal podcast where teammates interview each other to better understand their background, interests, habits, and then all employees can listen in once published.

name: Alex Lieberman ☕️
tweet: 5) "Cmd + Q" is codeword at ConvertKit.  It means that an employee is going off of Slack to do deep work and doesn't want to be bothered for a little while.
